      {
        "id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-the-eye-o.O-1%20Excel.pdf_12_3",
        "observed_type": "section_header",
        "canon_role": "section_header",
        "text": "Mini Toolbar and Shortcut Menus",
        "bbox": [
          0.2677902622701153,
          0.21502976213888345,
          0.6498127394420304,
          0.2311507938849152
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-the-eye-o.O-1%20Excel.pdf_12_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The Mini toolbar, which appears automatically based on tasks you perform (such as selecting text), contains commands related to changing the appearance of text in a worksheet. All commands on the Mini toolbar also exist on the Ribbon. The purpose of the Mini toolbar is to minimize mouse movement. For example, if you want to format text using a command that currently is not displayed on the active tab, you can use the command on the Mini toolbar - instead of switching to a different tab to use the command.",
        "bbox": [
          0.2640449533622683,
          0.2398255813311741,
          0.9213483211918523,
          0.34011627849770365
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-the-eye-o.O-1%20Excel.pdf_12_5",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "When the Mini toolbar appears, it initially is transparent (Figure 1-12a). If you do not use the transparent Mini toolbar, it disappears from the screen. To use the Mini toolbar, move the mouse pointer into the toolbar, which causes the Mini toolbar to change from a transparent to bright appearance (Figure 1-12b).",
        "bbox": [
          0.2640449455099148,
          0.3400297622089624,
          0.9232209653506548,
          0.40552325612989315
        ],
        "order": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-the-eye-o.O-1%20Excel.pdf_12_10",
